INTRODUCTION

The issues of the Epistolae that appeared in 1517 were the last to be published for nearly forty years, but in 1556 both parts of the work appeared sor the first time in a single volume.1 In the eyes of the new generation which had arisen it belonged to an age already half forgotten. The Reformation in Germany had run its course. The dawn that the Epistola& welcomed seemed fair enough, but it had ushered in a long day of storm. The blind and bloody struggles that ensued had exhausted the nation. In the im- pressive words of a recent writer, “Intellectually‚ morally, and politically, Germany was a desert, and it was called Religious Peace.” ²
